(526, 155, 'miscellaneous', '<strong>September 2011:</strong>\r\n\r\nDr. Hamann is elected as the Vice President of the American Political Science Association.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>August 2011:</strong>\r\n\r\nDr. Hamann’s book, The Politics of Industrial Relations: Labor Unions in Spain, is published.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>February 2010:</strong>\r\n\r\nDr. Hamann is nominated for the American Political Science Association’s Council (the top governing body) by APSA’s nominating committee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>January 2010:</strong>\r\n\r\nProf. Hamann serves as section co-chair for Teaching Political Science for the Midwest Political Science Association Meeting\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>November 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nProfessor Hamann, together with Philip H. Pollock  and Bruce M. Wilson, publishes “Who SoTLs Where? Publishing the Scholarship of Teaching and Learning in Political Science,” <em>PS: Political Science &amp; Politics</em> 42(4): 729-735.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>October 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nKerstin Hamann and John Kelly’s research on “General Strikes in Western Europe, 1980-2008,” is presented at the Instituto Juan March, Madrid, Spain.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>September 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nProf. Hamann, together with Philip H. Pollock and Bruce M. Wilson, publishes “Learning from ‘Listening’ to Peers in Online Political Science Classes.” <em>Journal of Political Science Education</em> 5(1): 1-11.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>March 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nHamann, with Miguel Martínez Lucio, publishes “Trade Unions and the Politics of Renewal in Spain in Historical Context: Making and Enacting Regulation and Representation.” In Craig Phelan (ed.),<em> Trade Unionism since 1945: Towards A Global History. Volume 1: Western Europe, Eastern Europe, Africa and the Middle East. Oxford and Bern: Peter Lang, pp. 121-154.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>February 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nProfessor Hamann, together with  Michelle Deardorff and John Ishiyama (eds.), publishes <em>Assessment in Political Science</em> Washington, D.C.: American Political Science Association.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>February 2009:</strong>\r\n\r\nHamann (with Bruce M. Wilson) presents “Online Learning: Models and Technologies” at the Workshop on “Creating Networks of Excellence for Qualitative Research in the Social Sciences: Creating a Training and Research Network in Sub-Saharan Africa,” Institute for Development Studies, Sussex University, UK.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>May 2008:</strong>\r\n\r\nProfessor Hamann is honored with the University Excellence in Undergraduate Teaching Award (1 campus-wide award)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>April 2008:</strong>\r\n\r\nProfessor Hamann is selected for an Excellence in Undergraduate Teaching Award, College of Sciences\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>March 2008:</strong>\r\n\r\nProfessor Hamann, together with,Bonnie N. Field (eds.), publishes  <em>Democracy and Institutional Development: Spain in Comparative Theoretical Perspective</em>, Houndsmill Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>November 2007:</strong>\r\n\r\nHamann presents “Corporatism, Social Pacts, and the Political Role of Unions and Employers” (with John Kelly) at the workshop on “Rethinking Social Partnership,” Hertie School of Governance, Berlin, Germany.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>October 2007:</strong>\r\n\r\nKerstin Hamann, Mark Rush, and Sebastian Royo edit and contribute a Symposium on “Putting Iberian Politics into the Undergraduate Curriculum,” <em>PS: Political Science &amp; Politics</em> 40(4): 687-688, which is featured on the cover page.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>May 2005:</strong> Dr. Kerstin Hamann and Philip Pollock have each been honored with a 2005 Scholarship of Teaching and Learning Award. The Scholarship of Teaching and Learning (SoTL) can be defined as research into teaching methods and effectiveness, with the ultimate goal of evaluating student learning. Each year, UCF sponsors 10 SoTL awards funded by the Office of Academic Affairs. Award recipients are chosen for the value and impact of their scholarship and creative efforts on the teaching and learning community.\r\n\r\n<strong>April 2005:</strong> Associate Professor Kerstin Hamann received the CAS College Excellence in Professional Service Award and the University Excellence in Professional Service Award. Dr. Hamann also was also awarded a University Scholarship of Teaching and Learning Award in April 2005.\r\n\r\n<strong>February 2005:</strong> Kerstin Hamann and Bruce Wilson helped set up a new journal, Journal of Political Science Education (JPSE), and they are part of that journal''s editoral board. The first issue of the JPSE was published in February 2005, and it also contains an article by these two faculty members and fellow professor Philip Pollock. [<a href="http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/titles/15512169.asp">Journal</a> ]\r\n\r\n<strong>January 2005:</strong> Associate Professor Bruce Wilson, Professor Philip H. Pollock and Associate Professor Kerstin Hamann received the American Political Science Association Undergraduate Education section''s Best Paper Award presented at the 2004 APSA meeting (The award was announced in March 2005 and will be presented in September 2005 at the APSA meeting). The paper title was "Teaching and Learning Online: Assessing the Effect of Gender Context on Active Learning". A revised version was subsequently published as Teaching and Learning Online: Assessing the Effects of Gender Context on Active Learning in the Journal of Political Science Education in January 2005.'),
